{"/service/ndnp/idhi/batch_idhi_bagrati_ver02/data/sn86091104/00279551084/1913082601/0151.xml":{"full_text":"THE RECORD\nPublished Tuesdays aud Fridays.\nO. B. and O. B. MOON, Publishers\nSubscription price, *2.00 per year In\nadvance. Advertising rates furnished\non request.\nEntered as Second-Class Matter June\n4, 1913. at the Post Office at Saint\nMaries,\nMarch 3, 1 879.\nIdaho, Under the Act of\nTUESDAY. AUG. 26 1913\nNormal Business and\nFinancial Conditions\nHave Returned\n(Capital News, Republican)\nThe period of financial depression\nla now at an end and an era of great\nprosperity Is again before the coun\ntry.\nThe Capital News has taken oooa\nslon frequently to point out to its\nreaders that reports Irom every form\nof Industry, tbe banks alone except\ned, showed that conditions are ripe\nfur a return of prosperity, factories\nand mills, we have shown, have or\nders ahead for a year and are run\ndug at full capacity except lo occa\nsional Instances where lalor troubles\nintervene to prevent operations; the\nrailroads ate mak ug greater profits\nthan at any time since the high profit\nperiod of 19c7; crop conditions ate\nreported satisfactory lo spite u( the\nrecent severe drought In Nebraska,\nKansas and Missouri, and pricea tor\nall forms of produce to the producer\ngive promise to being, not high, but\nquite satisfactory ou tbe whole.\nAnd now even the hunks where\nalone there was gloom aud dlsatfeo\ntlon ate aware that their gloom was\nunwarranted and that the panic they\ntried to produce will not develop and\nas a consequence they are extending\ntheir loans, releasing their high re\nserves and a general feeing of hope\nfulness is pevalent.\n\"Financial America, one of tn*.\nleadlng financial Journals of Wall\nstreet and llkewse an opponent of tbe\npresent national administration and,\ntherefore, not disposed to speak\nhopefully for the single purpose of\naiding a political favorite, In Its last\nIssue discussed tbe question thorough\nly from the standpoint of this conn\ntry aa well as from tbe standpoint ot\nforeign countries. It concludes that\nanother era of prosperity has return\ned. It says:\n\"The upward movement In the\nstock market has been continuons\npractically since Joue il, marking s\nperiod of over two mouths io\nthe prices ot many securities have\nbeen steadily established at higher\nfigures with hardly any loterniptlon\nin tbe sbape of a substantiel \u00bbaction\nOn June 10 and 11, the market was\nIn an unsettled condition benpuse of\nconstant allusion to tbe financial\nconditions io this country (Notice\ntbe effect ot tbe calamity howla ot\nRepublican politicians. Ed) and\nEurope with an absolute absence of\ntime money, offerings over the end of\ntbe year. Thera was then appreheo\n\u25a0ion ot a period of money stringency,\nresulting from the demands from the\nInterior for crop moving purposes\nand from projected financing here\nand abroad which was feared would\nbe too serious a strain on banking\naccommodation. The change In tbe\nsituation was coincident with the first\nannouncement of Secretary MoAdoo's\nfinancial proposltiona, which then\nwere to tbe effect that be was willing\nto accept savings bank collateral as\nsecurity tor additional bank circula\ntlon.\nwblob\nWe have here a frank admission\nfrom this bigb financial source that\nthe announcement of tbe secretary of\ntbe treasury had the effect that th\nsecretary expected and that we have\nadvised Oapital News readers would\nhappen, and thus Is vindicated tbe\ntheory that what tbe county needs la\na system of finance which will enable\nofficials to go direct to tbe people In\nstead of going direct to tbe gambling\nbankers of Wall street who, hereto\nfore, have had absolutely lu their\ncontrol tbe finances of tbe country\nand could make good times or hard\ntimes just as they desired for their\ngambliog operations,\nEngland bankers are not only sat\nisfied with tbe new development lo\ntbe financial eitnatioo in this coun\ntry because of this change In method\nand plan, but they are wondering\nwhy It should not be adopted as a\npermanent policy Instead of an ex\nceptlooal one.\nThe Londan financial correspond\nant of \"Financial America\" says;\n\"The announcement of the deposit\nof 160,900,000 of treasury fonda\nwith the western and soul hero nation\nal banks In the United Stales, coup\nled with tbe Intimation that further,\nheavy government balances would be'\ndeposited, If required, bas been re\neelved with relief In Loudon. In\n\u25a0pita of the movement of what prom\nlaes to be a record harvest In the\nstates. It Is now thought here that\ntheta will be much less autumn pres\nsure thao usual in New York; and\ndespite the opposition which. It is\nreported, has sprung op Id certain\nAmeroian banking circles against tbe\naction of tbe American treasury, the\nquestion is asked here, why this pol\nIcy ot luoreased government deposits\nshould not be a normal, Instead of\nan exceptional feature of tbe United\nStates' monetary autumn.\nEditorially tbe financial autboiity\nwhich is quoted above expressed even\nmore emphatically tbe Impi- ved coo\ndltloo Id financial circles and thus\nIndicates the removal ot tbe last bar\nrler to tbe return to normal ooudl\nttona which ought to prevail amidst\ns\nram\no\nn\u00a7 USED TO ADYETTUSD\nJJ\u00a9lhunis\u00aeini\nQ\nSSl\nYes We Bo All Kinds of IRepair Work and Guarantee It\nWEST END\nsuch encouraging crop and Industrial\nconditions. It says:\n\"Two months ago every discussion\nof tbe financial prospect wag tlnotnr\ned with pessimistic rbservatlons re\ngarding tbe strain on the world's\ncredit position. This strain has been\ndeveloping for a number of years and\nwould take as many years io remedy.\nNow, however, only a little later io\nthe summer, discussion which passes\nin Wall street Is lightened with tbe\noplnoo, cheerfully ventured, that tbe\nstrain on the capital markets of tbe\nworld has been relieved entirely, and\nthat the outlook is one which can be\nviewed without concern.\nReform Moves On\n(Article In The Commoner signed\nby W. J. Bryax.)\nTariff reform and currency reform\nare moving on, slowly but steadily,\nand with certainty of triumph. The\ntariff bill as It passed the boose was\na splendid measure\u2014the beat that tbe\ncountry has ever seen since the war.\nIt gives more relief to tbe taxpayers\nthan any previous democratic meas\nure would bave given,\never, is only natural, because tariff\nbills, like other bills, reflect public\nsentiment, and public sentiment to\nday U ready for a more radical re\nduction than would have been possi\nble thirty, twenty, or even ten, years\nThis, how\nthe bouse.\nstate tbe\nBut the senate, Instead of emascu\nlating the bill, as previous senates\nhave done,-has actually Improved It,\nand, it is bettor than wben It passed\nla difficult to over\n^icb tbe democratic\nHe deserve for tbe\n^^\u25a0differences have\nthe entire pai\n^fipport of the bill.\non final passage\n^Pdemocratlo sens\nleadry^\nniannbl\nbeen bar\nty brougl\nIt is eurV\nnot rnore^\ntors will o\nV\n\nbill, and It will\nse t\nnot be surprising ft, when tbe roll Is\ncalled, even tbe senators from Louis\niana vote \"aye,\" on the theory that,\ntaken as a whole, the bill will bring\nmure benefits to tbelr constituents by\ntbe reduction made, than free sugar\noau do harm.\nWhile the democrats ot the senate\nand bouse have duoe their duty man\nfully, the pr\u00e9sident deserves a large\namount ot oredltjfor tbe firm stand\nhe has taken In favor of a reduction\nthat will be substantial and far\nreaching in its effects. The country\nIs beginning to realize what it means\nto have a people's president\u2014a cham\npion In the White House who has\ncourage to fight their battles for\nthem, aud who knows not the word\ngarded as foothills, these three provl\nemus stand out like mountain peaks,\nIf the people can secure the three ad\nvantpgee named above, they can af\nford to accept any details that a ma\njorlty of the senate sod house may\nwrite Into tbe bill. A detail can be\nchanged when experience shows It to\nbejanwise, but a change lo [a funds\nmental principle Is mote difficult,\nTbe more this bill Is studied tbe\nmore widespread will be tbe feellug\nthat never since the civil war have\nthe people io general been so largely\nconsidered in the framing of a money\nmao.\n\"surrender.\nThe currency bill is not as far ad\nvanced as the tariff bill, but It Is\nsteadily gaining ground. The meas\nure favored by the president la under\nconsideration lo both bouses and\nthere Is now little doubt of its pass\nIn (act, It la likely to have a\nage.\nlarger majority lo both bouses than\ntbe tariff bill.\nThe tariff meaenre\nmust rely largely upon democratic\nvotes (or its success because It is\nmore purely a party issue; but party\nHues are likely to be disregarded to\nsome extent In the vote upon tbe\ncurrency question; the bill will gain\nrepublicans than It loses demo\nmore\norats.\nLet tbe readers ot The Commoner\nkeep in mind th.ee things:\nFirst\u2014Tbe bill recognizee tbe aov\nerelgn right of tbe government to Is\nsue mousy.\nSeooud\u2014The bill provides that tbe\npeople, through tbelr governmental\nagents, xhall rsgolate the issue ot the\ncurrency provided (or.\nThird\u2014The bill extends to state\nand national banks alike tbe help\nwhich tbe federal government offers\nin times of emeigeuoy.\nIt the details of tbe bill osn be re\nmeasure.\nAud to the president must be tbe\nthanks (or having thrown tbe tremen\ndous weight of hla Influence on tbe\npeople's aide. It is probable that the\nfact that be ie ao eastern man has so\nabled him to do more than a western\not southern man could have done on\nTbe\nder the same circumstances.\nWall street crowd Ja not able to ex\ncite tbe same (ear of him that It baa\nsuccessfully endeavored to\nagainst those who live beyond tbe\nAl.egbeniea and south of tbe Poto\naroute;\nLet ns rejoloe that times, condt\ntlona and circumstances ere oombin\nIng to strengthen the preaideot In bla\nfight aud to offer new hops to those\nwho have, for so many years been\ncombating the Influence, open and\nsecret, of \"tbe money power.''\nThere are other questions which\nwill demand tbe president's attention\nwhen tbe regular session opens, for\nthis work has just commenced, but\nwith two gr.at victories to bla credit,\nbis prestige will be Increased, and\nthat will be used in the people's\ncaose.\nThe Cow and the Hen\n(Little Logged off Lauda.)\nNot forgetting tbe danger of r\u00abpi\ntltloo, for we mean to hold fast to\nthe subject so long us tbe need for\nthe direction of Interest toward that\nsubject remains, we want to say the\ngreatest need of tbe Pacific Northwest\ntoday la earnest, energetic, scientific\nfarming. Many of the oommerolal\nbodies ot this part of the country are\ndevoting a large part of their efforts\ntoward tbe location of factoring. As\na matter of fact, this In a very large\nmeasure la wasted effort. The raw\nmaterial, generally speaking. Is not\nhere. The factory hands are an ab\nsent quantity, and lastly, there Is a\nvery limited market.\nEggs are selling today at 35 cents\na dozen and butter at 40 cents per\npound. Tbe kind of factories that\nare most needed aud the ones that are\nsure of success may be Instituted aud\noperated by tbe luveameut ot a tbous\nand dollars, and the factory owner's\nlabor, with that of hla family, on tbe\npayroll. Any man who will establish\nau incubator and brooder, which be\ncomes In a sense a ofaiukeu factory,\naud will operate hla own five acres of\nground, may be assured of success.\nThe same Hoe of argument, but cue\nthat will require more capital, would\nbe tor a newcomer considering a herd\nof cows as his factory turning out\ndairy products. If he does not re\nceive an Income ot one hundred dol\nlars per month from his ten cows,\nthere la something wrong either with\nthe news or with tbe factory man.\nA. N. Oarletoo met with an aool\ndent Friday that made It difficult for\nhim to get around for tbe past tew\ndays. He was coming from tbe mill\nand io crossing a wet place slipped\nonto an old sewer nlpe.\noff and came down\nHe slipped\nwith bis full\nwiegbt on hie aukle across the pipe\nAlthough do bonee were broken bis\nlimb was badly bruised and be has\nbeen quite lame since.\nt\nj\n\n\n\nj j\n\nPLUMBING\nand HEATING\nJOBBING A SPECIALTY\nPATRICK H. O'REILLY\nCall for an Estimate.\nOffice 156 College-St.\nSt. Maries New Store\n\nI\nj\nWallace Building.\nOne Block West of Post Office\nla now open and ready (or business with (all Hoe of\nNcw and Second Hand Goods\nIncluding Dressera, Beds, Ruga, Oarpeta, Curtains, Exten\nsion Tables, Chairs, Ranges, Stoves, Kitchen Cabinets and\nother articles too numerous to mention, which will be sold at\nSPOKANE PRICES\nOsll and examine our stock. Wo oau please you and save\nyou money. Freight paid to surrounding towns on all bills ot\nfifty dollars and over.\nO. U SAWYER, Manager.\nPhone I9*t\nWASHINGTON FURNITURE CO.\nNUMBER 2\nTHE GHEGK 7UBGOUNT\nWhat the check account will do (or yoor baaim\nGive you safety for yoor foods, without any risk of loss through\ncarelessness or theft.\nConvenience tor paying bills, small or largo, to other person at\nany time or place.\nAccuracy for every cent expanded.\nA complete record in all\ndetails.\nHelps you to save by pointing out tbe place and purpose of\nevery cent spent.\nFurnishes you a method (or running yonr buslneae systematical\nly, knowing at all times your standing.\nGives yuu a means tu trauaact business with other people, which\nthey will appreciate.\n\n\nLumbermens State Bank\n\ni\nI\nSURPLUS, S3.SOO.OO\nO. O. HAKVEY, Vice President.\nCAPITAL, S2S,000.00\nJ, H. EDWARDS, President.\nO. M. SARGENT, Cashier.\nNOTIOK\nNotice Is hereby given that sealed\nproposals will be received by tbe Oity\nClerk of the Olty of St. Mariea, at\nhie office in said city upon tbe 27th\ndayof Angnst, 1913, at eight o'clock\np. m., for tbe construction of a sewer\